494
00:26:02,194 --> 00:26:04,517
So first off, if you want to do this,

495
00:26:04,998 --> 00:26:06,880
you've got to have a very solid base game.

496
00:26:08,147 --> 00:26:10,468
And the trick there is to make the game feel absolutely

497
00:26:10,508 --> 00:26:13,709
complete, even if you don't own any expansions.

498
00:26:14,909 --> 00:26:17,030
It's going to feel, it's going to have to feel like a

499
00:26:17,070 --> 00:26:18,790
complete experience, basically.

500
00:26:18,850 --> 00:26:20,210
Or it'll come back to bite you.

501
00:26:20,230 --> 00:26:24,392
And you're going to have some fun core loops.

502
00:26:25,952 --> 00:26:28,613
That's what you should focus your efforts on, making sure

503
00:26:28,653 --> 00:26:32,194
that the base game you release has excellent core loops that

504
00:26:32,234 --> 00:26:33,034
are addictive and fun.

505
00:26:34,165 --> 00:26:37,608
And you can save all those darlings, all the extras, for

506
00:26:37,628 --> 00:26:40,931
later, because you can rest easy in the knowledge that you

507
00:26:40,971 --> 00:26:43,113
will probably release a lot of expansions.

508
00:26:46,476 --> 00:26:49,318
Of course, you also need to prepare for that fact.

509
00:26:50,079 --> 00:26:52,421
You should think about all the expansions you want to release

510
00:26:52,561 --> 00:26:54,983
over at least the first couple of years.

511
00:26:55,363 --> 00:26:58,086
So you should have design outlines for that and the code

512
00:26:58,126 --> 00:26:58,906
base to support it.

513
00:27:02,484 --> 00:27:07,486
And if you boil it down to two principles, when you design

514
00:27:07,566 --> 00:27:11,927
features for expansions that people pay for, principle

515
00:27:11,987 --> 00:27:14,248
number one is that they have to be visible.

516
00:27:14,688 --> 00:27:17,370
It has to have a visible impact, or people will not

517
00:27:17,450 --> 00:27:20,351
understand that you put a lot of effort into it.

518
00:27:20,791 --> 00:27:24,072
So no matter how much work you do under the hood, it's not

519
00:27:24,092 --> 00:27:25,833
going to be well received unless it's

520
00:27:25,913 --> 00:27:26,693
immediately visible.

521
00:27:27,885 --> 00:27:28,946
So here's an example of that.

522
00:27:29,166 --> 00:27:32,970
We added something called Aegis to Europa and Rosalis 4.

523
00:27:34,611 --> 00:27:36,653
Once you install that expansion, you

524
00:27:36,673 --> 00:27:38,815
can immediately see in the main interface

525
00:27:38,855 --> 00:27:40,456
that there's a little thing there.

526
00:27:40,717 --> 00:27:43,219
You're in this age of reformation, for example.

527
00:27:45,330 --> 00:27:51,336
The other main principle is that good expansion features should be atomic in a way. They

528
00:27:51,356 --> 00:27:56,662
should be standalone, unentangled, and independent from as many systems as you can

529
00:27:56,682 --> 00:28:03,809
possibly make them. This can be very hard, of course, but if you can't make the features

530
00:28:03,909 --> 00:28:09,214
atomic and standalone, you should put them in the free patches and updates instead.

531
00:28:11,897 --> 00:28:15,200
One big no-no, another tempting thing, as a designer especially,

532
00:28:16,041 --> 00:28:19,844
is to add a paid feature that you don't

533
00:28:19,884 --> 00:28:22,866
want to build on in a subsequent expansion after that.

534
00:28:23,747 --> 00:28:24,748
That's going to be very tricky.

535
00:28:24,768 --> 00:28:27,270
You're going to be limiting the number of people who actually

536
00:28:27,330 --> 00:28:32,854
can buy and enjoy that second upgrade to those features.

537
00:28:33,755 --> 00:28:35,056
So don't paint yourself into a corner.

538
00:28:38,622 --> 00:28:41,204
And with that in mind, we have found

539
00:28:41,224 --> 00:28:43,867
that there are certain types of features that are

540
00:28:44,067 --> 00:28:46,950
excellent material to make paid.

541
00:28:48,992 --> 00:28:52,375
First off, features that add new ways of playing,

542
00:28:52,715 --> 00:28:54,877
of achieving old goals in a new way.

543
00:28:56,239 --> 00:28:58,721
Say that you take territory through military means

544
00:28:58,781 --> 00:29:00,463
in the base game, but then you add

545
00:29:00,483 --> 00:29:03,045
a way of doing it diplomatically in an expansion as well.

546
00:29:04,694 --> 00:29:10,539
progression is super good as well. If you can add a system where you can level up or gain new

547
00:29:10,599 --> 00:29:17,646
ranks or rank up in some old system, that's also perfect. It's pretty stand alone atomic.

548
00:29:19,176 --> 00:29:23,697
And then there's customization stuff, like we made a DLC for Crusader Kings 2.

549
00:29:24,458 --> 00:29:28,539
It's a barber shop, basically, where you can change hair and beard of your character.

550
00:29:29,159 --> 00:29:35,341
And it's a little thing, but it's kind of cool and it's extremely standalone and not

551
00:29:35,401 --> 00:29:36,662
entangled in anything else.

552
00:29:37,462 --> 00:29:38,082
Purely cosmetic.

553
00:29:39,770 --> 00:29:45,752
And then there's faction unlocks, which is, it's not just us doing this, I think other companies

554
00:29:45,772 --> 00:29:52,533
have also found that it's perfect for this. And the reason is that there is a risk when you add

555
00:29:52,573 --> 00:29:57,874
more features to the game, that you get feature creep, the interface gets cluttered with new

556
00:29:57,974 --> 00:30:04,876
things, but if you do faction unlocks that doesn't happen because it adds a different way of

557
00:30:04,916 --> 00:30:08,217
playing the game with mutually exclusive interfaces basically.

558
00:30:10,236 --> 00:30:12,219
And then you can do quality of life UI things.

559
00:30:13,040 --> 00:30:14,623
And I have an example of that coming up.

560
00:30:17,167 --> 00:30:19,751
So here's an example of a faction unlock in Crusader

561
00:30:19,771 --> 00:30:20,812
Kings 2 on release.

562
00:30:21,453 --> 00:30:22,796
You could only play Christians.

563
00:30:24,057 --> 00:30:25,460
And that had a distinct play style.

564
00:30:26,647 --> 00:30:30,350
But then with expansions we added things like Muslims in sort of Islam.

565
00:30:31,532 --> 00:30:35,035
And with this expansion, the old gods, we made it possible to play pagans.

566
00:30:35,496 --> 00:30:37,237
And it's a completely different experience.

567
00:30:38,178 --> 00:30:41,421
The Christians mostly play nice and abide by diplomatic rules.

568
00:30:41,501 --> 00:30:45,565
They have to use... they have to have a reason to go to war and all that boring jazz.

569
00:30:46,683 --> 00:30:49,405
But the pagans, they're all about raiding and pillaging

570
00:30:49,445 --> 00:30:52,688
and just declaring war, taking concubines, having a good time.

571
00:30:54,349 --> 00:30:56,391
We also added 200 more years to the gameplay,

572
00:30:56,691 --> 00:30:57,772
which was quite appreciated.

573
00:30:58,573 --> 00:31:02,516
But the cool thing about this is if you don't play as the pagans,

574
00:31:02,996 --> 00:31:03,877
it's the same old thing.

575
00:31:04,578 --> 00:31:06,700
So the pagans are a different way

576
00:31:06,960 --> 00:31:08,181
of experiencing the same game.

577
00:31:12,667 --> 00:31:13,508
Here's another example.

578
00:31:13,908 --> 00:31:16,229
It's the diplomatic macro planner

579
00:31:17,050 --> 00:31:18,410
from European Missile List 4.

580
00:31:19,831 --> 00:31:22,693
It basically gathers up all diplomacy in one place,

581
00:31:23,233 --> 00:31:24,353
and it was very appreciated.

582
00:31:24,934 --> 00:31:28,115
So it's a new interface that you get with this expansion

583
00:31:28,155 --> 00:31:28,816
mandate of heaven.

584
00:31:30,449 --> 00:31:32,150
But it's very separate from everything else.

585
00:31:32,350 --> 00:31:33,811
It's just a convenience thing.

586
00:31:34,852 --> 00:31:35,792
You don't have to have it.

587
00:31:36,513 --> 00:31:37,973
The game works just as well without it,

588
00:31:38,714 --> 00:31:40,855
which means that it's standalone and very modular.

589
00:31:41,716 --> 00:31:43,317
So a perfect feature for a paid expansion.

590
00:31:46,606 --> 00:31:49,147
And there's one more example of progression.

591
00:31:50,708 --> 00:31:53,549
Instalaris, which has a really cool tech system.

592
00:31:54,229 --> 00:31:55,910
The technology system Instalaris is basically

593
00:31:55,930 --> 00:31:57,370
a collectible card game almost.

594
00:31:58,131 --> 00:32:00,832
So it's very easy to slot in new technologies.

595
00:32:01,952 --> 00:32:05,513
And what we did here is basically we added a new layer

596
00:32:05,834 --> 00:32:08,935
of late game technologies for progression and ranking up.

597
00:32:11,016 --> 00:32:13,217
And in this case, it's very visible in some cases,

598
00:32:13,237 --> 00:32:16,238
like the Planet Destroyers and the Titan class spaceships.

599
00:32:20,103 --> 00:32:21,864
All right, so those are some good types of features

600
00:32:21,884 --> 00:32:23,385
that you can actually charge money for.

601
00:32:24,826 --> 00:32:26,707
But there are also bad features.

602
00:32:26,787 --> 00:32:29,908
And trust me, we've made plenty of these as well,

603
00:32:30,709 --> 00:32:31,389
plenty of mistakes.

604
00:32:32,730 --> 00:32:36,112
So you can do these things, but the point

605
00:32:36,192 --> 00:32:37,873
is you cannot charge money for them.

606
00:32:39,654 --> 00:32:41,995
So you shouldn't try to make core gameplay changes that

607
00:32:42,115 --> 00:32:45,557
alter the experience for players who have the expansion.

608
00:32:46,338 --> 00:32:47,058
That's a big no-no.

609
00:32:48,098 --> 00:32:53,343
You shouldn't try to make or charge money for minor improvements. Balance and bug fixes of

610
00:32:53,423 --> 00:32:59,868
course should be free. And you should not try to make features that mess with a thousand

611
00:32:59,988 --> 00:33:03,551
other features in the game. That's a pretty bad idea.

612
00:33:06,343 --> 00:33:08,324
So here's an example from CK2.

613
00:33:10,025 --> 00:33:12,726
In Crusader Kings 2, armies are not standing around on the map,

614
00:33:13,426 --> 00:33:16,787
and they are mobilized or called up when you need them.

615
00:33:17,067 --> 00:33:18,548
So they're peasant levies, essentially.

616
00:33:19,408 --> 00:33:21,129
But I thought it would be a really cool idea

617
00:33:21,309 --> 00:33:23,930
if the professional troops that actually existed at the time

618
00:33:24,670 --> 00:33:26,471
could also be represented in the game somehow,

619
00:33:26,691 --> 00:33:30,552
and that as the eras progress, the peasant levies

620
00:33:30,572 --> 00:33:32,613
would be phased out, and people would start

621
00:33:32,713 --> 00:33:33,853
using retinue troops more.

622
00:33:35,149 --> 00:33:37,831
However, while this was well received,

623
00:33:38,372 --> 00:33:42,134
it also messed with the core gameplay in significant ways.

624
00:33:44,196 --> 00:33:46,377
It's completely upset the balance of warfare,

625
00:33:46,658 --> 00:33:48,239
if you had the expansion or not.

626
00:33:48,819 --> 00:33:50,400
And it was also a feature that we really

627
00:33:50,420 --> 00:33:52,942
wanted to build on in subsequent expansions,

628
00:33:52,982 --> 00:33:55,004
but we couldn't because we painted ourselves

629
00:33:55,384 --> 00:33:55,925
into a corner.

630
00:33:59,251 --> 00:34:07,474
And here's a more recent example, a Blitz combat tactic from Hearts of Iron IV, which caused pretty much an uproar on the forums.

631
00:34:09,735 --> 00:34:16,837
In itself, it should be pretty suitable as a paid feature, but it was kind of a minor thing.

632
00:34:16,877 --> 00:34:22,539
It was one combat tactic among many, and it was perceived that this should have been part of the base game.

633
00:34:23,605 --> 00:34:25,628
It was also unfortunate that it was called Blitz.

634
00:34:26,250 --> 00:34:28,554
You know, it's pretty iconic for a World War II game

635
00:34:28,894 --> 00:34:30,838
to have a Blitz command or combat tactic.

636
00:34:31,920 --> 00:34:33,563
So it kind of backfired on us.

637
00:34:36,447 --> 00:34:39,287
We've also done some entangled features.

638
00:34:40,427 --> 00:34:43,608
This is a system we added in EU4 called Estates.

639
00:34:45,088 --> 00:34:47,249
It's basically internal political factions

640
00:34:47,529 --> 00:34:49,269
that create gameplay for you as a ruler.

641
00:34:49,509 --> 00:34:52,470
You need to keep these political factions happy,

642
00:34:53,050 --> 00:34:55,450
or they will start causing you all kinds of troubles.

643
00:34:56,150 --> 00:34:57,511
But they can also give you bonuses.

644
00:34:58,811 --> 00:35:01,071
The problem with this feature, or one of the problems with it,

645
00:35:01,731 --> 00:35:04,832
is that it kind of messes around with every other thing

646
00:35:05,012 --> 00:35:05,432
in the game.

647
00:35:06,344 --> 00:35:10,908
whenever we release something new, we have to consider, well, what will happen to the

648
00:35:10,968 --> 00:35:16,753
estate's mechanic if we do this, etc. So, pretty bad idea. Should have been free.

649
00:35:20,632 --> 00:35:21,912
Which brings us to free features.

650
00:35:22,653 --> 00:35:23,793
There is nothing wrong with this.

651
00:35:24,473 --> 00:35:27,835
And I think we spend at least 50% of our development time

652
00:35:27,855 --> 00:35:29,716
actually doing free features.

653
00:35:31,417 --> 00:35:34,078
As long as you have a strong theme for your expansion,

654
00:35:34,918 --> 00:35:36,999
they are perceived as a whole thing.

655
00:35:37,800 --> 00:35:40,541
The free and the paid part make for one experience.

656
00:35:41,301 --> 00:35:43,002
And that's also how I see it as a designer.

657
00:35:44,769 --> 00:35:48,671
I really ideally want people to kind of mix them up and not

658
00:35:48,751 --> 00:35:50,171
know what is free and what is paid.

659
00:35:50,471 --> 00:35:52,712
Doesn't really work that way, but you can dream.

660
00:35:54,033 --> 00:35:57,114
So free features, using them, you

661
00:35:57,154 --> 00:35:59,435
can replace old mechanics that you don't like much.

662
00:35:59,995 --> 00:36:01,696
You can mess around with the core gameplay.

663
00:36:03,237 --> 00:36:05,558
And people will still perceive that the game

664
00:36:06,018 --> 00:36:09,059
is kept fresh and cool, and you're doing interesting shit.

665
00:36:12,478 --> 00:36:15,251
So everything I said was bad in a paid feature, you can

666
00:36:15,713 --> 00:36:16,878
probably do as a free feature.

667
00:36:19,863 --> 00:36:26,547
There are some other pitfalls that don't have to do specifically with the types of features.

668
00:36:27,907 --> 00:36:35,011
You should remember to stick to what the game is. This is also something we've forgotten sometimes.

669
00:36:36,532 --> 00:36:44,157
And what is the game? Well, it's partly what we think it should be, what we thought when we created the game originally.

670
00:36:44,217 --> 00:36:46,098
But it's also what the players think that the game is.

671
00:36:47,891 --> 00:36:52,075
And the biggest mistake you can make

672
00:36:52,515 --> 00:36:54,897
is probably add new restrictions on players.

673
00:36:56,118 --> 00:36:59,381
Now, there is a case to be made that our games, at least CK2,

674
00:37:00,222 --> 00:37:02,163
is hard to learn and easy to master.

675
00:37:03,144 --> 00:37:06,627
And that's kind of the pyramid upside down, right?

676
00:37:07,468 --> 00:37:10,430
So I had the brilliant idea that let's crank up the challenge

677
00:37:10,470 --> 00:37:11,551
and make the game a bit harder.

678
00:37:12,874 --> 00:37:17,617
So we added defensive alliances and other things to the game

679
00:37:17,737 --> 00:37:20,498
that were supposed to crank up the challenge.

680
00:37:21,439 --> 00:37:23,420
But people just felt that they'd been

681
00:37:23,460 --> 00:37:24,741
put in a straitjacket instead.

682
00:37:24,761 --> 00:37:26,622
And that's not a good place to be.

683
00:37:27,283 --> 00:37:31,185
So don't mess with agency, the player's freedom to act.

684
00:37:33,127 --> 00:37:35,188
And then there's, of course, feature overload and UI

685
00:37:35,208 --> 00:37:35,508
clutter.

686
00:37:36,568 --> 00:37:42,532
And it's a challenge because it completely contradicts the high visibility requirement

687
00:37:42,592 --> 00:37:43,793
of paid features, right?

688
00:37:44,734 --> 00:37:49,518
But if you have a lot of visible features, what are you going to end up with?

689
00:37:49,798 --> 00:37:51,959
Well, it's going to be a pretty overloaded interface.

690
00:37:54,321 --> 00:38:01,546
Another huge mistake is to, as developer, think that, yeah, I like the Black Sheep Turks.

691
00:38:01,887 --> 00:38:03,568
You know, we should expand on that experience.

692
00:38:03,888 --> 00:38:04,809
It's an awesome faction.

693
00:38:06,424 --> 00:38:09,025
But unfortunately, most players will not see it that way.

694
00:38:09,525 --> 00:38:10,545
They have their preferences.

695
00:38:10,605 --> 00:38:13,646
And we know that there are certain countries that are a

696
00:38:13,686 --> 00:38:14,886
lot more popular than others.

697
00:38:15,387 --> 00:38:15,787
Germany.

698
00:38:16,647 --> 00:38:20,608
Germany, Prussia, the Confederate States of America,

699
00:38:20,848 --> 00:38:24,889
the Eastern Roman Empire, all of these are super popular.

700
00:38:25,449 --> 00:38:26,830
For some reason, don't ask me why.

701
00:38:27,957 --> 00:38:31,280
But when we do an expansion about India or something, yeah,

702
00:38:32,541 --> 00:38:32,681
no.

703
00:38:33,582 --> 00:38:35,364
So just don't go there.

704
00:38:35,945 --> 00:38:36,725
It's a sad fact.

705
00:38:39,849 --> 00:38:44,773
So what actually, what do players value?

706
00:38:46,175 --> 00:38:49,178
Well, initially we thought that, hey, let's

707
00:38:49,198 --> 00:38:50,239
look at Steam review scores.

708
00:38:51,255 --> 00:38:52,135
That's a great metric.

709
00:38:53,636 --> 00:38:57,757
And it was a pretty good metric originally, but then less and

710
00:38:57,777 --> 00:39:01,519
less so over time as there was more and more rage about our

711
00:39:01,539 --> 00:39:02,819
DLC model particularly.

712
00:39:04,000 --> 00:39:07,441
So there's a correlation between steam review score and

713
00:39:07,501 --> 00:39:10,762
actual revenue, but it's weaker than you might expect.

714
00:39:12,163 --> 00:39:17,605
So as designers, we look more at actual revenue now than we

715
00:39:17,625 --> 00:39:18,605
do the steam review scores.

716
00:39:20,355 --> 00:39:24,256
And we also came up with a neat little formula or spreadsheet

717
00:39:24,696 --> 00:39:29,058
that we employ to estimate the value for money

718
00:39:29,338 --> 00:39:30,478
for our expansions.

719
00:39:31,339 --> 00:39:32,839
So these are some CK2 expansions.

720
00:39:34,400 --> 00:39:38,121
And we've divided up the features into different sizes.

721
00:39:39,121 --> 00:39:41,422
And each size gives you a different sort of score.

722
00:39:42,423 --> 00:39:46,364
So we then sum up that score, and we divide it

723
00:39:46,424 --> 00:39:47,404
by the price point.

724
00:39:48,357 --> 00:39:55,819
and then we get a pretty arbitrary value for money. It works pretty well. We want that value

725
00:39:55,859 --> 00:40:02,182
for money value to be at 2 or above ideally. But as you can see some of our more popular

726
00:40:02,222 --> 00:40:08,984
expansions are actually way below that or a bit below that. So old gods had 1.8, it still did

727
00:40:09,004 --> 00:40:14,626
extremely well. So the flaw with this formula is it doesn't really consider the free

728
00:40:14,686 --> 00:40:17,427
features that we release along with the paid ones.

729
00:40:19,018 --> 00:40:23,521
I mean, I know for a fact that the Reapers do, which didn't really contain that much paid

730
00:40:23,561 --> 00:40:30,906
content, was extremely well received, mostly due to the free stuff. So people keep mixing this

731
00:40:30,986 --> 00:40:37,890
up and it's to our advantage, of course. So we're still working on improving this formula or

732
00:40:37,950 --> 00:40:38,411
spreadsheet.

733
00:40:41,226 --> 00:40:43,469
And now we come to Johan's part of this presentation.

734
00:40:43,950 --> 00:40:46,653
So sadly, I'm not going to do it justice.

735
00:40:47,575 --> 00:40:50,819
But it has to do with other types of challenges that are

736
00:40:50,839 --> 00:40:52,381
not related to design specifically.

737
00:40:55,405 --> 00:40:56,507
About the architecture.

738
00:40:59,080 --> 00:41:01,722
Well, the code base will keep evolving all the time.

739
00:41:02,683 --> 00:41:04,784
And that's interesting in many ways.

740
00:41:05,485 --> 00:41:08,187
But it's going to help, at least in our position it

741
00:41:08,227 --> 00:41:10,149
helps, because we have so many live projects.

742
00:41:11,330 --> 00:41:13,311
We can do a lot of improvements in the engine.

743
00:41:13,351 --> 00:41:15,713
We have the close of its engine, and we have a middle

744
00:41:15,733 --> 00:41:16,754
layer called Gemini.

745
00:41:16,774 --> 00:41:20,717
And if you can do improvements there, it's going to benefit

746
00:41:20,817 --> 00:41:21,538
all the games.

747
00:41:24,362 --> 00:41:29,286
And Johan really wanted to stress that you should keep the code simple and readable and not

748
00:41:29,506 --> 00:41:35,491
over engineer it. And that's very important for us because in our organization we have to

749
00:41:35,551 --> 00:41:40,515
move the programmers around a lot and you know they need to understand the code pretty much at

750
00:41:40,575 --> 00:41:42,556
a glance. So don't get too clever.

751
00:41:44,012 --> 00:41:45,673
You also got to keep the code maintainable.

752
00:41:45,693 --> 00:41:49,776
And I know one thing he wanted to bring up was a simple

753
00:41:49,796 --> 00:41:50,317
little trick.

754
00:41:50,657 --> 00:41:54,840
If you have a get function, for example, you can pass

755
00:41:54,880 --> 00:41:56,902
along a text string as an argument or

756
00:41:56,982 --> 00:41:59,023
pointer to get the tooltip.

757
00:41:59,364 --> 00:42:00,605
So you only have one function.

758
00:42:01,806 --> 00:42:02,466
You following, Chance?

759
00:42:02,526 --> 00:42:02,726
No.

760
00:42:04,568 --> 00:42:07,470
You only have one function to work with.

761
00:42:07,490 --> 00:42:09,292
And you don't have to have a separate tooltip function.

762
00:42:10,930 --> 00:42:15,394
And you should try to have a clear programming guideline

763
00:42:15,774 --> 00:42:17,655
or standard that everyone follows.

764
00:42:20,418 --> 00:42:22,139
As for the technology itself, well, it's

765
00:42:22,179 --> 00:42:23,260
a virtual file system.

766
00:42:23,420 --> 00:42:25,802
We treat our DLCs exactly like mods.

767
00:42:26,622 --> 00:42:28,664
They're pretty much the same thing as far as the game is

768
00:42:28,704 --> 00:42:29,104
concerned.

769
00:42:30,465 --> 00:42:32,427
They're packages that are treated as modular changes.

770
00:42:33,845 --> 00:42:36,908
And you can toggle them on or off at load time, which is

771
00:42:36,948 --> 00:42:37,369
convenient.

772
00:42:37,409 --> 00:42:43,254
So if you buy House Lords or full plate music or whatever,

773
00:42:43,854 --> 00:42:45,636
you can turn it off if you don't like it or if you get

774
00:42:45,676 --> 00:42:45,956
tired.

775
00:42:49,459 --> 00:42:51,421
And then there's the process, the project

776
00:42:51,481 --> 00:42:53,483
management of it all.

777
00:42:54,624 --> 00:42:56,185
And it's very important, of course, to plan ahead.

778
00:42:57,700 --> 00:43:01,542
should have the design ready in time. The designers should be,

779
00:43:01,842 --> 00:43:05,403
you know, one step ahead all the time. And you should have a

780
00:43:05,443 --> 00:43:10,905
scalable UI that is easy to work with and make room for more

781
00:43:10,925 --> 00:43:13,906
stuff because you will add more stuff to the UI. It's

782
00:43:13,946 --> 00:43:19,708
guaranteed. And it's important to remember that you have to

783
00:43:19,748 --> 00:43:20,909
repay tech debt.

784
00:43:22,005 --> 00:43:24,787
We have a pretty aggressive schedule

785
00:43:24,967 --> 00:43:26,508
when it comes to releasing these expansions

786
00:43:26,548 --> 00:43:28,289
and we don't have an infinite amount of people.

787
00:43:28,909 --> 00:43:30,691
So sometimes we have to cut some corners

788
00:43:30,891 --> 00:43:34,233
and accept the fact that we will have to do some hacks

789
00:43:34,273 --> 00:43:35,374
and hard-coded solutions.

790
00:43:36,455 --> 00:43:38,376
And these accumulate and get worse over time.

791
00:43:39,577 --> 00:43:42,639
So it's worthwhile to take some time to catch up.

792
00:43:43,039 --> 00:43:44,480
And we usually schedule a couple of weeks

793
00:43:44,720 --> 00:43:49,243
in between certain expansions to catch up on our tech debt.

794
00:43:53,233 --> 00:43:56,898
Most importantly though, you need to understand your players.

795
00:43:58,660 --> 00:44:02,284
And if you can use reasonable metrics, do so.

796
00:44:02,465 --> 00:44:04,647
You know, if you have telemetry, use it.

797
00:44:04,848 --> 00:44:06,169
If you don't have telemetry, add it.

798
00:44:08,472 --> 00:44:10,455
And you should listen to your hardcore fans.

799
00:44:12,377 --> 00:44:14,578
to some degree, I suppose, don't listen to them too hard

800
00:44:15,158 --> 00:44:17,860
because they are a pretty vocal minority.

801
00:44:18,381 --> 00:44:20,322
But as long as they keep it constructive and positive,

802
00:44:20,542 --> 00:44:22,724
you should listen to their stories and what they tell you.

803
00:44:24,665 --> 00:44:25,986
And you will understand them, probably,

804
00:44:26,006 --> 00:44:28,568
if you play the game yourself.

805
00:44:29,148 --> 00:44:31,810
And sadly, not all people actually play the game

806
00:44:31,830 --> 00:44:33,011
and enjoy it.

807
00:44:34,472 --> 00:44:36,693
So how can you expect your players to do so?

808
00:44:41,262 --> 00:44:49,748
Right, so if I were to summarize this somewhat unfocused

809
00:44:50,689 --> 00:44:56,913
subject, it would be keep your design modular and stand alone.

810
00:44:58,194 --> 00:45:00,375
And this is for the paid features, of course.

811
00:45:02,117 --> 00:45:03,017
And you should think about.

812
00:45:03,855 --> 00:45:09,761
player perceptions more than the time you spend developing

813
00:45:09,821 --> 00:45:11,903
something or how hard or complex it is.

814
00:45:12,664 --> 00:45:15,266
The only thing that matters is how players perceive it.

815
00:45:15,867 --> 00:45:19,130
So remember to make your features visible and to be

816
00:45:19,170 --> 00:45:20,672
perceived as giving high value.

817
00:45:22,994 --> 00:45:24,776
And you need to have a maintainable architecture.

818
00:45:26,791 --> 00:45:28,852
There's probably something here to add on the business

819
00:45:28,872 --> 00:45:29,633
side of things as well.

820
00:45:30,153 --> 00:45:31,995
I think that you touched on something that's really

821
00:45:32,015 --> 00:45:35,858
interesting in the sense that we built the company by having

822
00:45:35,898 --> 00:45:39,701
a very transparent and open and very close dialogue and

823
00:45:40,042 --> 00:45:41,543
relationship with a lot of our fans.

824
00:45:41,603 --> 00:45:42,584
We try to listen to them.

825
00:45:43,044 --> 00:45:46,047
We have our forums that have over a million active users.

826
00:45:47,928 --> 00:45:51,751
And what's happened over the years is that not only has

827
00:45:53,875 --> 00:45:56,957
a lot more people have come into the Paradox ecosystem

828
00:45:57,217 --> 00:46:00,760
that are not familiar with the games or don't...

829
00:46:01,540 --> 00:46:03,021
Everyone has their different types of stories.

830
00:46:04,462 --> 00:46:07,163
So the vocal minority is...

831
00:46:08,104 --> 00:46:11,906
They get a critical mass in their voices.

832
00:46:11,926 --> 00:46:14,168
That's heard in a completely different way today.

833
00:46:14,248 --> 00:46:17,690
And it's heard differently because they also have tools

834
00:46:17,870 --> 00:46:18,931
which allows them to get...

835
00:46:19,772 --> 00:46:25,775
hurt. So on one hand, I mean, we're getting a lot of complaints on the DLC model. On the

836
00:46:25,856 --> 00:46:31,098
other hand, we have more people than ever that not only buy the stuff, but they keep

837
00:46:31,198 --> 00:46:38,983
buying it. And, you know, we end up with a silent majority that are in the game, enjoying

838
00:46:39,023 --> 00:46:42,645
the features, and not shitposting on the forums.

839
00:46:44,035 --> 00:46:46,338
So there's always this balance of trying to find,

840
00:46:47,099 --> 00:46:49,002
how do we keep in touch with the players

841
00:46:49,122 --> 00:46:50,484
and listen to what they have to say

842
00:46:50,945 --> 00:46:52,186
and balance that out against.

843
00:46:53,613 --> 00:46:57,396
what we're doing and what the silent paying majority is doing, because at the end of the

844
00:46:57,456 --> 00:47:00,678
day, they are the people we need to please, because they keep paying us.

845
00:47:02,079 --> 00:47:05,702
If somebody doesn't agree with some of our practices, it's somewhat hard.

846
00:47:06,263 --> 00:47:10,026
There's another interesting point that I think we could make as well.

847
00:47:10,066 --> 00:47:15,970
I took the point here, is that I can't stress enough, and I've said it a million times,

848
00:47:16,010 --> 00:47:17,211
but it's really what I love.

849
00:47:17,251 --> 00:47:18,072
It's the business model.

850
00:47:20,700 --> 00:47:24,662
Games that follow these give us a robust protection from

851
00:47:25,462 --> 00:47:26,343
changes in the market.

852
00:47:26,383 --> 00:47:27,563
And I'll give you a good example.

853
00:47:28,223 --> 00:47:30,924
When Steam rolled out their refund policy, and for those

854
00:47:30,984 --> 00:47:33,966
of you not familiar with it, the Steam refund policy said

855
00:47:33,986 --> 00:47:36,587
that if you played the game for less than two hours, you

856
00:47:36,607 --> 00:47:38,107
could refund it, no questions asked.

857
00:47:38,748 --> 00:47:41,048
And this was rolled out without informing a single

858
00:47:41,149 --> 00:47:43,910
publisher or developer, as far as I know, and nobody I've

859
00:47:44,010 --> 00:47:45,370
asked had heard of it before.

860
00:47:46,291 --> 00:47:50,637
And they even had a big grace period of six months back, you could just refund anything.

861
00:47:52,179 --> 00:47:57,105
If you had a game, let's say you had an indie game that was very narrative and story driven,

862
00:47:57,146 --> 00:48:02,152
you could start and finish it in less than two hours, you were utterly and completely screwed over.

863
00:48:02,873 --> 00:48:04,775
by that policy change from Steam's side.

864
00:48:05,215 --> 00:48:06,917
It's ultimately a good policy change.

865
00:48:06,977 --> 00:48:10,361
It protects the consumer and makes our positions as gamers a lot better,

866
00:48:11,041 --> 00:48:13,684
but that developer's business model is completely screwed.

867
00:48:14,625 --> 00:48:16,026
And when it comes to a Paradox game,

868
00:48:16,066 --> 00:48:19,350
well, good luck getting past the main menu in two hours.

869
00:48:21,734 --> 00:48:27,859
So it's a silly example of how the business model or the way

870
00:48:27,899 --> 00:48:31,201
we do things actually allow us a fair bit of protection

871
00:48:31,642 --> 00:48:32,602
from stuff on the outside.

872
00:48:33,123 --> 00:48:35,044
I think a lot of us have seen the

873
00:48:37,448 --> 00:48:43,090
The image of Mona Lisa being cut into small pieces and they're selling the pieces in separate

874
00:48:43,110 --> 00:48:49,833
pieces as an analogy of how games are destroyed today and discrete parts being sold.

875
00:48:50,693 --> 00:48:55,015
Pieces that people should be in the game and belong in the game.

876
00:48:55,295 --> 00:49:00,237
And I don't want to get into this big discussion about entitlement, but it's something that

877
00:49:00,277 --> 00:49:02,738
we end up thinking a lot about and talking a lot about.

878
00:49:03,178 --> 00:49:04,319
It's also feasibility.

879
00:49:05,059 --> 00:49:08,261
If that was true, it would take us 10 years to develop a game.

880
00:49:08,281 --> 00:49:11,563
And it would look bad at the time we released it.

881
00:49:12,243 --> 00:49:15,485
And ultimately, I think that whenever

882
00:49:15,545 --> 00:49:19,908
we have a good balance between quality of life improvements

883
00:49:19,948 --> 00:49:24,291
that we would give away for free and do screw-ups where we charge

884
00:49:24,331 --> 00:49:26,932
for features that feel like they should be in the game,

885
00:49:27,453 --> 00:49:28,573
that's where we get more hate.

886
00:49:28,994 --> 00:49:32,555
But ultimately, I mean, the game is called Crusader Kings, not Muslim rulers.

887
00:49:33,155 --> 00:49:39,877
So I don't feel that necessarily if we charge, if we put that into the kind of Mona Lisa DLC like we described,

888
00:49:40,198 --> 00:49:43,839
that's not necessarily a comparison that I feel is kind of fair.

889
00:49:44,519 --> 00:49:48,801
But it's, perception is ultimately reality and I think that...

890
00:49:49,661 --> 00:49:55,284
The issue we have today, perhaps, with a lot of people that are upset with the DLC model,

891
00:49:55,384 --> 00:50:02,387
is a lack of us explaining the rationale for why the model exists,

892
00:50:02,907 --> 00:50:08,230
and what, ultimately, what kind of additional value they get thanks to this model.

893
00:50:09,030 --> 00:50:11,991
A lot of people might just now simply just not want it.

894
00:50:12,876 --> 00:50:16,058
Other people in the community complain that we just do too

895
00:50:16,098 --> 00:50:18,519
much stuff that's nice, and they want everything, but they

896
00:50:18,539 --> 00:50:19,180
can't afford it.

897
00:50:19,320 --> 00:50:21,061
And we should stop doing stuff, therefore.

898
00:50:21,541 --> 00:50:23,442
But I have a hard time getting behind that argument.

899
00:50:25,143 --> 00:50:27,565
Coming back to my original statement about the key metric

900
00:50:27,625 --> 00:50:32,028
of having a number in the main menu that tells you how much

901
00:50:32,068 --> 00:50:35,390
you spent per hour of entertainment, I think we

902
00:50:35,410 --> 00:50:37,191
should really do it every time the

903
00:50:37,231 --> 00:50:38,211
complaints become too loud.

904
00:50:38,792 --> 00:50:40,553
I even argue that we should increase

905
00:50:40,593 --> 00:50:41,273
the price of the game.

906
00:50:42,057 --> 00:50:44,899
And this is, of course, everyone just wants to shoot me when I say this.

907
00:50:45,319 --> 00:50:48,140
But arguably, if you bought Crusader Kings six years ago,

908
00:50:49,001 --> 00:50:51,422
it's a much, much, much better game today.

909
00:50:51,462 --> 00:50:53,603
And we're still only charging 40 bucks for it.

910
00:50:54,003 --> 00:50:56,744
People go nuts when we don't lower the price of the game.

911
00:50:57,505 --> 00:50:58,505
I think we should raise it.

912
00:50:59,426 --> 00:51:00,986
It has arguably more value.

913
00:51:01,026 --> 00:51:04,148
And the concept of we should lower the price of things over time

914
00:51:04,208 --> 00:51:06,209
because it's old.

915
00:51:08,675 --> 00:51:09,556
it doesn't hold up to me.

916
00:51:10,117 --> 00:51:11,618
People, I think, look at how,

917
00:51:11,999 --> 00:51:13,220
you know, and this is the reality,

918
00:51:13,280 --> 00:51:17,144
we have to deal with people's and players' behaviors

919
00:51:17,604 --> 00:51:19,646
and conditioning through other games,

920
00:51:20,207 --> 00:51:22,089
and then they apply that to the lens of our game.

921
00:51:22,861 --> 00:51:24,622
And it doesn't really jive to me.

922
00:51:25,282 --> 00:51:27,784
But again, I can't change perception and reality.

923
00:51:27,824 --> 00:51:29,524
I can just try to explain the model

924
00:51:29,945 --> 00:51:32,186
and show them how they get additional value.

925
00:51:32,286 --> 00:51:34,547
And I can, black and white, show why

926
00:51:34,987 --> 00:51:38,769
we would have never been able to create all this cool content

927
00:51:39,369 --> 00:51:42,831
if it wasn't for the fact that we'd created all the DLC.

928
00:51:44,812 --> 00:51:45,052
Cool.

929
00:51:46,293 --> 00:51:48,714
I don't think we have anything else to add to that.

930
00:51:48,794 --> 00:51:50,575
We'd be happy to take questions.

